text.tspan: General notes:
- When Step loads a theme it knows which elements to draw by id of the element. In most
cases the corresponds to the name of the object on Step palette (in english translation).
- In Inkscape you can set element id using "object properties" dialog available from context
menu of the element.
- If graphics for an object should be composed of several SVG elements, just group all elements
together (using Group tool) and and assign required id to the whole group.
- Items with non-special ids have no meaning for Step and can be used as comments for artists
or as sketches for future elements.
Elements with constant on-screen size:
- These element are always painted by Step with the same size regardless of zoom level.
- This size is defined by size of an item in this SVG file.
- In Step these items will always be positioned according to their geometrical center.
If you want something other (for example a pin can be painted like a real 3d pin visible at
some angle and it should be positioned according to the end of the needle) you could group
you item with another invisible item to make the center of the group coincide with the end
of the needle.

CircularMotor
Spring. It will be stretched by the Step to required length, but its width will be always preserved.
- WARNING: In the future Spring will be reimplemented and will require different graphics
Stick. It will be stretched by the Step to required length, but its width will be always preserved.
- WARNING: In the future Stick will be reimplemented and will require different graphics
Arrows.
- Each arrow consists of a body and a head.
- For linear arrows body length will be stretched, all other sizes will be preserved.
- For circular arrows all sizes will be preserved, but the body will be clipped.
- A head will be centered around the end of the body. If you want something else, see
general notes at the begining of the file.
- Names should follow the following patterns:
LinearArrow_body_<name of the property>
LinearArrow_head_<name of the property>
CircularArrow_body_<name of the property>
CircularArrow_head_<name of the property>
- Currently arrows are used for the following properties:
LinearArrow: velocity, acceleration, forceValue
CircularArrow: angularVelocity, angularAcceleration, torqueValue
